A longer finger than the ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer.
Men whose finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously exposed to a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday in the British Journal of Cancer.
This is related to the level of male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, especially in men up to sixties,” said the study’s co-author, Ros Eeles, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health burdens, she added.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in the UK traced more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer, but at the same time 3,000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same likelihood of prostate cancer was considered as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and fingerfingers were equally long.
However, in men whose finger is longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, and in men up to 60 percent by 87 percent.
The proportion of the length of the two mentioned fingers, which are formed already in the prenatal age, obviously reflects the different levels of gender hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone is equivalent to a longer fingerprint.
Earlier research has shown that just testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, the leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that this study is flightly known to him, yet he does not consider the ratio between finger length and cancer risk to be "fullly proven".
