Global Plan for the Renewal of Lighting
The UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (FCKW), which corresponds to one-third of the additional reduction that needs to be achieved to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun to compensate for the absence of compulsory reduction commitments by the industrial countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of the lighting-released FCKWs to the Earth would be avoided if the white-glowing pearls, which so far still represent a 50 to 70% monopoly on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better, by light diodes (LEDs).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the world’s transportation park’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year the major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global FCC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt should be removed from this balance to stabilize the climate rise by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 to prevent it from falling out of control.
In the whitening pears, 95% of the energy is empty in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produces light.
With the compact lighting lights, the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED lights, this energy need is reduced twice.
The compact lighting lights last between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED candles, such as those that the manufacturer Philips has launched this week – this company has, by the way, participated in the UN study – have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a whitening candle, giving an indication of the savings of the exchange plan that is intended to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that the completely new lights deliver very little heat, they can also work with a regulatory resistance.
And they do not contain any silver.
Several specialists have shown that compact lighting pears have reserves as they contain silver and that therefore they need to be discharged as a special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for producers to provide a reception site.
The main source of silver emissions on the planet, however, according to the report, is not the compact lighting pipe, but rather the coal power plants that emit significantly more silver to produce the electricity lost by the whitening pipe.
Only in the United States, these coal power plants explode 25,000 tons of silver annually.
The report describes in detail the profits that each country would earn thanks to this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in purchasing electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is equivalent to 3.5 coal plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion dollars.
